Invasive species can have profound ecological and economic impacts (
 Pimentel et al., 2000; 
 Pyšek and Richardson, 2010), so there is considerable benefit to studying the drivers of invasion to inform control and biosecurity programs to mitigate their influence. Assessing trait evolution in introduced species is important because functional traits can influence demographic parameters essential for invasion success. Consequently, there has been considerable interest in identifying trait differences between native and invaded ranges, to try and understand if and when evolutionary changes might causally drive invasion (
 Thébaud and Simberloff, 2001; 
 Hinz and Schwarzlaender, 2004; 
 Bossdorf et al., 2005; 
 Felker-Quinn et al., 2013; 
 Hodgins et al., 2018).
